neighborhood_overview: Little Italy/Chinatown. Amazing food and shopping right outside the door.  Within a five-ten minute walk, you will find yourself in Nolita, Soho, Tribeca, the Lower East Side-- you'll find an incredible variety of bars, restaurants and shopping in these areas.   Very close to Two Bridges-- a section in Chinatown where lots of new and exciting places are popping up. Tourist attractions: walk to lower Manhattan (911 memorial, Wall St. Battery Park, etc.), the Brooklyn Bridge, the New Museum, Tenement Museum, MOCA, easy subway access to other places.   Walk to the East River (via Catherine Slip) is 10 minutes.  Safe.
notes: Please read the below list and make sure you are OK with everything before booking.  Feel free to ask questions.  -Street-facing room (therefore some noise, as is typical in NYC) -Walk-up building (2 floors) -The stairwell and hallways of the building are not impeccably maintained  -The mattress is quite firm  -The bed is American "full" sized (not queen) -No  laundry -Directly above a restaurant with sidewalk seating  -No AC in common areas -No TV -Self check-in by picking up key at a lockbox down the street
transit: Walking:  Chinatown and Little Italy: all around.  Soho and Nolita: 2-3 minutes. Lower East Side and Tribeca: 8-10 minutes East Village, West Village and Financial Districts: 15-25 minutes. Dumbo and Brooklyn Heights: 45-50 minutes (via the Manhattan Bridge or Brooklyn Bridge).  Transit: N,Q,R,6,J,Z - Canal Street (2 minute walk) B,D - Grand Street (5 minute walk) B,D,F,M - Broadway-Lafayette (8 minute walk) 2,3 - Canal Street (8 minute walk) A,C,E - Canal Street (10 minute walk)
access: All common areas are available for your use/comfort/enjoyment.  Kitchen:  Fully stocked with most cookery you could imagine, stainless steel appliances, dishwasher, coffee, tea, spices, oil.  No microwave.  Dining Area: Daytime sunlight, large table for a proper meal, doing work, etc. Living Area: Couch, reading chair, keyboard, books, periodicals.  No TV. Bathroom: sunny good water pressure, renovated, new, modern, toiletries, hairdryer, iron.  WIFI: Strong and reliable. Note that there is no AC in the common areas of the apartment.
interaction: I am very available by text, phone and email.  But, I am out of the apartment from early morning until evenings most weekdays.  Weekends vary (during the summer, I am often out of town/away).  If we're in the apartment at the same time,  I'm happy to share a beer, meal, chat or whatever, but zero pressure to hang if you prefer to do your own thing. I've lived in New York most of my adult life and have lots of ideas and suggestions-- let me know what you like and want to know about.
house_rules: No laundry list of rules.  Be reasonable, kind, respectful, human.  Treat my home like your home.  I don't operate as a business.  I'm one person, with an extra room in my apartment and I'm interested in accepting guests that will treat my home as theirs and communicate with me as needed.  I'll send you a welcome note a couple days before the start of your booking that should have all the details you'll need (re locating the key pick-up, my apartment, Wifi codes, local amenities, tips on using the shared spaces).  CHECK-IN:  Weekdays: I can usually personally greet and orient you after 7 PM (or before 6AM).  If you are arriving at a different time, it will be a self check-in by picking up a key at a cafe nearby.   On certain occasions, if you are arriving after 11 PM, you may have to pick up your key at a location that is about 15 minutes away (walking) or 5 minutes away (by cab).   Weekends:  Schedule varies. I will try to meet you and orient you in person if possible.  CHECK OUT: Bef

host_about:
Hi, I'm Shelia, but my friends call me Lia. I am a culinary professional born and raise on the streets of New York City. Currently I do a little food writing and plan on becoming a food critic in the near future as I love to dine all over the city. 
 I would say that I am a citizen of the world. I have been to over 20 countries and plan to reach my goal of 100 countries in the next 20 yrs. Wish me luck. Out of some of those countries I have resided for long periods of time in Belize, Central America; Mexico; and the Bahamas in the Caribbean. I hope to one day live in South East Asia, preferably Cambodia as they are big in the volunteerism industry. Actually for the last few years I have been residing in Belize volunteering and traveling throughout Central America. 
  I speak a few languages, which include French Spanish and obviously English. I'm really not so good at the second languages but I get by and I could probably hold a good intense 10 minute conversation before you tell me to just stop trying.. lol.
  I am big on anthropology and love to meet new people and find out about they're cultures and experiences. I guess I would say that I am a big people person. I love the whole concept of Airbnb because it allows me to do what I love best... travel and socialize. As a host I understand what its like to visit new or even revisit interesting places and so I like to be as accommodating to my guest as much as possible.
  I think that's pretty much it about me. Oh no wait, I also have a pretty good sense of humor.  " knock knock" ... "who's there?" ... "you're airbnb guest!" Ok maybe not so funny but I try.

interaction: I like to meet and greet my guests when they arrive, with a brief walk-through of the bedroom and the apartment, and to offer my advice about nearby cafes, restaurants and places to see. house_rules: No smoking, drugs, parties or pets. notes: This is East Harlem (El Barrio, Spanish Harlem) Please take that into consideration when you book. There is a grand mix of cultures here, and I have lived here for over a year with no issues. Please do not ask me if its safe... I am a single woman in E. Harlem. I am a smart cookie... I wouldn't live anywhere unsafe.

host_about:
Hey everyone! I'm Veronica! I'm 29! I love to travel and see new places, but I also love going "home" which is usually NY, TX, and Cali! Yup. All 3. I got use to moving around. I served 5 years in the Navy and did some deployments too. I'm fine, however! I just a never lost that sense of adventure. 

I've been to many states, many countries, and sailed many seas. I'm honest and respectful. I love walking about the city to take in the sights and eat as much as possible.

But i was born and raised in Houston Tx! Yup... I have cowboy boots and I can lasso. But I love the city of Houston! We are known for our quick wit and southern hospitality. The people I usually travel with are also from Houston! We love seeing new places and experiencing as much as possible. All my friends are good people doing the right things, so it's nice to break away from life and let loose! 

Thanks! 
V

Although small in size they are centered around a spacious common lounge area with free WiFi. Bathroom is shared. And very clean.
space: We use the profits from the guest rooms here to provide hot meal for homeless people on the streets of New York City. If you're willing to come to help with the meal distribution for two hours for one day of your visit (from 9:30AM until 11:30AM) we can offer you a lower price. No smoking, no alcohol, no meat products are allowed here. And no spitting on the floor :) If this works for you - contact us. neighborhood_overview: This neighborhood is called: Chelsea.      There are literally hundreds of small unique restaurants, shops, book stores, galleries, theaters and pubs in Chelsea.  You will find, gently-strolling, pedestrian traffic at all hours of the day of evening.    Chelsea is not a dark, or dangerous area.   It's a neighborhood that's full of life.        Many artists, musicians, writers, actors, FIT students, other graduate students, similar intelligentsia, and creative people live in Chelsea.  I think you'll like it here.       You can get anywhere in New York City quickly and easily from here.         The subway station is two blocks away (a two minute walk).
notes: Our place is vegetarian: no meat, no fish, no eggs, no spitting on the floor :)
transit: JKF Airport, Newark Airport, and La Guardia Airport all offer fast, direct, public transportation to Penn Station in Manhattan.  Penn Station is a three minute walk from here.
access: Spacious breakfast area with free wifi. Bathroom is shared. It had several shower cabins, toilet cabins and sinks.
interaction: We're there 24/7 to make sure everybody is happy!
house_rules: Our place is vegetarian: no meat, no fish, no eggs, no spitting on the floor :)
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
Hi everyone! I'm Alex. My good wife Zina and I will try our best to host you nicely in our cute little vegetarian bed and breakfast place in the heart of East Village or in our freshly renovated interfaith hostel facility in Chelsea. Please contact us, we are here to serve you!
We use the profits from the guest rooms here to provide hot meals for homeless people on the streets of New York City. You may have seen us on the side of Tompkins Square park distributing hot vegetarian meals to the people in need. Since the money you give us for your room is financing the meal distribution program, just by staying here, you're already helping to support this program. 
But if you'd like to personally come out to help with the meal distribution for two hours (from 9:30AM until 11:30AM) for one of the days of your visit, we will offer you the bed and breakfast guest room for a special price.
Sincerely,  Alex, Zina and their little daughter Gourangi

neighborhood_overview: Harlem is known to have its unique identity and vibe in Manhattan both culturally and fun wise! There is so much to explore from Civil War history to the Harlem Renaissance of jazz and entertainment. There are 4 amazing sprawling parks within walking distance. You'll have a real choice of satisfying your mood...stay in the neighborhood with a choice of great restaurants offering American (Kitchenette) Ethiopian (Zoma), Japanese (Jado), French (Maison Harlem; Cedric's), Italian (Max SOHA; Lido), and Soul Food (Red Rooster, Manna's, Sylvia's, & Melba's); We are also a quick walk to Central Park, Columbia University, the historic Apollo (email hidden)e Upper Westside is broad, vast and very interesting. Have fun!!!!
notes: Best way to get to our apartment from JFK  The best way to get here would be by the Subway. It is very easy. When you leave the Terminal, just take the Airtrain to Howard Beach Station. It will Cost you 5 dollars to exit. From there you can get a Metro Card to use the Subway, your options are: pay per ride 2.75, 7 day unlimited 31, monthly 116. Just take the Manhattan Bound "A" Train and get off at 125th street (about 1 hour). from there we are once block away West, at the corner. 143 morningside ave Apt#2 From Penn station 34th street / Port Authority 42nd, Just take the uptown Bound "A" Train and get off at 125th street (about 1 hour). from there we are once block away West, at the corner. 143 morningside ave Apt#2 From La Guardia Airport. Take the M60 bus to St. Nicolas Ave. Right infront of the Apollo and ACBD subway. we are once block away West, at the corner. 143 morningside ave Apt#2

neighborhood_overview: The Area Lower East Side (LES)  •Russ & Daughters 179 E Houston St. This is an institution if you like bagels, been open over 80 years.  •Tapeo 29 and Salt Bar Cnr Clinton and Stanton. These are two great bars with great bar food.  •Clinton St Baking Company 29 Clinton St. Be sure to go early on a weekday to avoid the lines for brunch.  •Katz Delicatessan 205 E Houston. Lots of tourists but one of the most famous delis in NY.  •Whole Foods 96 E Houston. Great organic supermarket with a nice food court upstairs. We also have a Key Food for basic and less expensive groceries, located on Avenue A and 4th Street. Further south at the corner of Avenue A and Houston is Union Market which has a butcher and good quality fish.  Nolita  •Fonda Nolita 267 Elizabeth St. Some of the best tacos and Margaritas around. Gets busy early.  •Café Habana 17 Prince St. Very famous café.  •Bar Bossa 232 Elizabeth St. Great Brazilian restaurant with a relaxed vibe. Soho  Great people watching and great shoppi
transit: Transport  •There are 2 subway stops within 5-8 short blocks from the apartment. The F is at  Houston and 1st Ave and the L is located at 14th street and 1st Ave.  •For the airport you can take public transport or a car service/cab. It usually runs 35 from Laguardia and 65 from JFK. I typically use Dial (PHONE NUMBER HIDDEN).  • Cabs are everywhere in NY and take all cards. Be sure to get in the cab first before telling them where you are going, by law they have to take you. The best spot to get a cab is on 1st Ave or A.  • We of course have Uber, Lyft, Juno, and VIA app car services as well. I'm a big fan of VIA's shared ride service.  •There are Citibikes at the corner of 6th St. and B, just one block east of the apartment.  Busy Bee Bikes just in front of my building also has  bicycles for rent.

If fashion/design is your thing, Dover Street Market and ABC Carpet & Home are nearby as well as some supe
neighborhood_overview: It's safe, and the "hottest" in NYC right now, sometimes called "Madison Park" - basically at the border of Gramercy and Flatiron. In nice weather you can walk anywhere - ten minutes to Chelsea, East Village, etc. The architecture and the park are beautiful, the streets and sidewalks are not overly crowded and they’re clean. There is a good mix of national brand stores for when you know exactly what you want and small boutique shops for when you want something unique. Curry Hill is a block to the east, with great Indian food and groceries... Eataly is a block to the west, with everything under the sun... and tons of great gourmet restaurants nearby. Not to mention the original Shake Shack. And Dover Street NY, for the fashionistas.
transit: The 6 train and the N/R are right nearby, so you have the rare treat of being east but able to get to the west side pretty easily. Express buses run up and down Park and Madison Avenues, great for museum trips. There's a Citibike dock right across the street.
access: Guests have full and exclusive access to the apartment, which comes stocked with pantry basics, coffee and tea, paper products, a hair dryer, designated closet space, umbrellas.
interaction: Guests enjoy total privacy although I am just a text or email away should you need anything. Note that I do live in this apartment - it's not a "vacation property."
house_rules: The main rule is the Golden Rule - please treat the apartment and building with respect. In addition, no parties and no overnight guests that haven't been previously approved by me. A book in the apartment provides check-out procedures, wireless access codes, appliance instructions, arrival/departure instructions etc. Also there are takeout menus, my own neighborhood guide and several other city/neighborhood guides.

neighborhood_overview: The neighborhood around my home is a protected historic Harlem neighborhood . Several churches with Harlem's famous gospel choirs are within walking distance. Many movies and TV shows are filmed in this neighborhood because of its historical "feel"--if you're lucky, you might get to see a movie being made! New restaurants are opening at a rapid pace . Amsterdam is becoming known as "Restaurant Row. We are 4 blocks from Broadway, which offers more new restaurants offering Mexican, Italian, and pub food to small local ethnic restaurants serving Dominican and Ecuadorian specialties. And yes, McDonalds and several pizza places are nearby if you crave fast food! The church around the street has many festivals throughout the year--maybe you'll be lucky enough to see one during your visit! There are two parks nearby, and we are a short subway ride or walk to Central Park/ Hudson pier
notes: Please ask me questions if anything is unclear.
transit: Our house is a short walk to 3 different subway lines, and you can be in Midtown Manhattan--Broadway theaters, Times Square, Rockefeller Center, Fifth Avenue--within 20 minutes, door-to-door. A 30-40-minute subway ride brings you to trendy neighborhoods like Chelsea, Greenwich Village, Soho, and Tribecca. Even Brooklyn is within easy reach if you're adventurous! We are convenient to all three New York airports, Penn Station (the main train station) and the main bus terminal. There are plenty of cabs on 125 street.
access: Guests who wish to cook may use our kitchen any hours you wish. The dining room is yours to use whenever you want. Your  bedroom will be the living room & you will be given your space . In the evening you will probably be out enjoying New York's restaurants, theaters, and other attractions, you have full access to television if you'd like when ready . Please remember that the bathroom is a SHARED space, so please keep it neat and clean, as those who share it will do for you. There is a mirror and good lighting in your room, and we ask that you use that rather than the mirror in the bathroom fix your hair, put on makeup etc. in order to make the bathroom more available to everyone.
interaction: I may or may not be present during your stay and will be happy to answer your questions about the house, the neighborhood and the city. We provide you with information about the neighborhood and room, with recommendations for local restaurants etc. Otherwise, we basically leave our guests alone to come and go as they wish--you can have as much or as little contact with you as you want. You do not have to be back at the house by a certain time of night.

This fashionable and friendly neighborhood is composed of narrow streets, picture-perfect window displays, and sidewalk cafes that invite you to indulge in a cup of fine espresso. Easily walkable and cozily quaint, Nolita faces no competition when it comes to cool hotspots.

neighborhood_overview: Chelsea is a truly special neighborhood in Manhattan because of its art galleries, the High Line, the restaurants, the convenient public transportation, the beauty of the Hudson River, the gorgeous architecture, and the sense of community shared by the residents.
notes: Due to complications with receiving packages, we cannot receive deliveries for Airbnb guests. Please do not ask to have packages delivered before or during a reservation. Thank you:)
transit: Public transportation is among the best in our immediate neighborhood. Also, getting to/from the three airports is very easy. From LGA, take the Q70 LTD bus (i.e., the express bus to Roosevelt St). At Roosevelt, transfer to the E subway toward Manhattan (total cost 2.50). From JFK, take the AirTrain to Jamaica Station. Transfer to the E subway toward Manhattan (total cost 7.50). From EWR, take the AirTrain to the airport train depot. Transfer to the NJ Rail to Manhattan's Penn Station (total cost app. 13.00 per person). Then, take the E subway downtown one stop, or take a taxi to our home. You can also walk from Penn Station if the weather is nice. From the E subway train, exit at 23 Street station in Manhattan. Walk two blocks to Tenth Ave. We live near the northwest corner of Tenth Ave and 23 St.
access: Guests enjoy access to a private bedroom, private bathroom, the shared kitchen, and shared living room.
interaction: As much or as little as our guests like. We will cross paths occasionally in the kitchen, however :)
house_rules: Please treat our home as you would have others treat your own. You are welcome to come and go as you please (i.e., no curfews). The kitchen and living room are at your disposal. No entertaining outside guests, smoking, or playing loud music. The use of illicit drugs is strictly forbidden. Use of the clothes washer is available with our supervision and at a cost of 7 per load (regretfully, we found this measure necessary after our machine was accidentally broken by a guest). Our building has stairs and is therefore not suitable for small children.
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about: Along with Ed (my better half, pictured on the right), I strive to build a growing base of happy and loyal AirBnB clients. We're both fairly quiet guys: I have a doctoral degree and enjoy researching/writing, and Ed is a retired dentist now working in Manhattan real estate. We're very tidy, laid back, and respectful of guests' desire for the same. We're also very proud of New York City and are always happy to share our knowledge of the city's history and offerings. Traveling to world capitals and exotic places is our passion: I speak French and Portuguese fluently, and Ed speaks Spanish. We absolutely love hosting guests from all over the world, and we're always happy to interact with guests as much or as little as they like, so conversation over a bottle of wine is always welcome!

neighborhood_overview: The corner of Dyckman and Broadway is considered the new "South Beach North". Trendy restaurants of all kinds are punctuated by local ethnic cuisine alongside a new Starbucks; the same for the music, dancing, clubbing and the hooka craze! The public library, schools, playgrounds and numerous parks tempers the night life, but this is a bustling neighborhood with plenty to do. Fort Tryon Park and other local parks offer hiking, biking and amazing views of the Hudson River (only 3 blocks away). Atop the mountain is the Cloisters and  the New Leaf Cafe with spectacular panoramic views; hard to believe you are still in NYC! The locals are colorful and festive; the famous Marina Restaurant brings in celebrities and music, but 'restaurant row' along Dyckman is also what makes dining and entertainment exciting in this charming neighborhood. This is a neighborhood to 'experience'. The 24 hour grocery across the street saves the day...
notes: This an extremely safe, clean courtyard building with security cameras and on-site superintendent. The laundry room and garbage room are safe and clean. The archway entry separates the building area from the busy street beyond.
transit: The A train/subway adjacent to the building means a quick ride downtown into mid town or lower Manhattan; super convenient and an express train part way. A second subway line is only 4 blocks away. Time Square is about 20 minutes, lower Manhattan in 30. Located at the upper tip of Manhattan Island where the East and West side are closest together means getting to the airports is super easy and bypasses mid-town traffic; a recent late night pick up at LaGuardia clocked in at 20 minutes each way! Newark is a straight shot over the George Washington Bridge, about 40 minutes. Local cabs and car services are readily available.
access: Bedrooms being rented, living room, kitchen, office, bathrooms, breakfast nook, dining area, hallway and entry.
interaction: We offer a high level of privacy and are off premises as much as possible during your stay; however NY law may require the presence of the tenant. We request no discussion with tenants in the building except the Superintendent on premises in case of emergency.
house_rules: The building houses many interesting tenants; many are elderly and there is an unusual number of retired musicians in residence, including some famous faces you'll recognize! We do not like to disturb the tenants with loud noise, late night music or other things that would disturb any neighbors.  The apartment is cleaned thoroughly after each visit and checked for nasty things like bedbugs (necessary these days) but we require a security deposit in case of property damage aside from normal 'wear and tear'.  Food garbage must be handled properly and removed frequently. We have no bugs or mice and hope to keep it that way with  your assistance!

description: Large private bedroom in Manhattan apartment. Located in the neighborhood of Inwood, close to the express A & 1 trains, lots of local restaurants, bars and cafes. 30 minutes to Times Square. 5th floor of walkup apartment - no elevator, but less noise. Nathan and Brock have a wonderful apartment that they are happy to share with you. You'll be staying in the room while one of them is away. The room has a twin bed and a queen size sofa bed. There is fast wifi, a TV with a Blu Ray player and Apple TV. You will have access to the hall, bathroom, kitchen and bedroom. Either Nathan or Brock will be your main contact and host during your stay. Inwood is in Northern Manhattan above Washington Heights. Being further north provides larger apartments and a more neighborhood feel, but quick access to midtown. There are two large parks close by - Inwood Hill Park & Fort Tryon Park. The Cloisters (Medieval museum) is on the top of Fort Tryon Park and is part of the Metropolitan (MET) Museum system.
neighborhood_overview: Inwood is in Northern Manhattan above Washington Heights. Being further north provides larger apartments and a more neighborhood feel, but quick access to midtown. There are two large parks close by - Inwood Hill Park & Fort Tryon Park. The Cloisters (Medieval museum) is on the top of Fort Tryon Park and is part of the Metropolitan (MET) Museum system. There are many local restaurants, cafes and bars along Broadway or Dyckman St. There's a Starbucks as well as local places for coffee (Darling Coffee or Indian Road Cafe). Inwood is known for being a very Dominican neighborhood with many residents originally from the Dominican Republic. It's a great place to call home.
notes: FYI, the apartment is on the 5th floor of a walkup building. This means that there is no elevator. However, this also means that it is quieter at night.
transit: The A (express) and 1 (local) trains are close at the Dyckman or 207th St. stops. They can both get you to the Upper West Side or Times Square in 20-30 minutes! You can also easily hail a cab or get an Uber. If you are coming from an airport, I would suggest LGA. It is much closer to us.
access: You will have access to the hall, bathroom, kitchen and bedroom.
interaction: Either Nathan or Brock will be your main contact and host during your stay.
house_rules: No smoking and no pets.

We have a wonderful Saturday Farmer's Market, the famous medieval museum at the Cloisters, views of the Hudson, and plenty of low key local bars and restaurants. You can also visit the spot where the island was first bought nearby. We call it Upstate Manhattan!
notes: This is a great location for parents or friends coming to visit students at Columbia or Fordham. Fordham is a 20 minute bus ride away on the Bx12, and Columbia is 20 minutes on the 1. My family loves being able to stay with me in Manhattan, and we all love the easy commute to school events. For the convenience and price it's a win-win.  Otherwise, the thing to note about Inwood is that it's 30 minutes to midtown and about 40 minutes all the way downtown, so if you're visiting NYC keep in mind that it's easy enough to get everywhere, but you won't be in and out of the house in between site-seeing destinations.  My apartment is an older building, and in all older buildings there are quirks. I have consistent hot water and decent water pressure, but sometimes the shower takes a while to calibrate. The furnaces are all working, but sometimes they make noise. If that is the kind of thing that will bother you a lot, this is probably not the right place for you to stay.
transit: There is lots of great public transit. My apartment is a half city block from the A train (runs down Broadway on the west side), 3 blocks from the 1 train (runs downs 8th avenue on the east side), several Manhattan buses downtown, and the Bronx 12 (Bx12) Select Service Bus into the Bronx.
access: Guests are free to use the kitchen, and are welcome to use the living room as a sitting area if I am out and not using the space. There is Wifi, but no cable TV.
interaction: I prefer to let guests take the lead on how much they want to socialize. I'm a Ph.D student at Fordham, so some weekends I am busier with work than others, but if I'm free then I would be happy to chat and/or show off the neighborhood!
house_rules: I'm pretty easy going. Just have basic respect for my things (i.e.,) don't break them, don't spill on them). To avoid that I would appreciate having no food or dark beverages in the bedroom. Beer/wine is okay- enjoy the city!
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
Hello! 

I am a graduate student at Fordham University, and I just moved to New York in 2013. I'm from Chicago originally, and I am loving plugging into the beat of a new city. I'm currently working on my Ph.D in philosophy, so that's an interest, but I also love to travel, eat, and read non-philosophy. My favorite form of exercise is Ashtanga Yoga, my favorite food is everything, my favorite night out is comedy and drinks, jazz, or wine classes. I also like to study languages, so I'm currently learning French for my degree, and I spent my undergraduate years learning Arabic and traveling in North Africa and in the Middle East. If only Arabic wasn't so hard, I might have gotten better at it!

I hope to make sure that your stay is comfortable and that you have everything that you need. If you would like to stick around the neighborhood to get the Inwood experience, then I'm happy to show you around. But if you're doing your own thing, then by all means do NYC your way.

ps- I don't have a solo picture of me that's recent, so I'm the one in the middle of my profile picture! There I'm in France waiting to see some Bastille Day fireworks last summer.

neighborhood_overview: Washington Heights is a quiet, serene place and the perfect home base in a city that can sometimes be frantic. Across the street from my building is the beautiful J. Hood Wright Park with views of the George Washington bridge. Home to families, people in the performing arts, and doctors and nurses who work at nearby NYP, the neighborhood has a residential feel.  There are several grocery stores within 2 or 3 blocks of where I live, and a 24 hour Rite Aid is nearby. I recommend the sports bar Coogan's, Irish bar Le Cheile, and Italian restaurant Saggio as the best places to hang out locally. For most nightlife you're probably going to want to explore elsewhere, but the express train makes that easy.
transit: The A express train is less than two blocks from my front door and will take you to Times Square in 20-30 minutes. The 1 line is within walking distance, too, and it can get you to the Upper West Side/Central Park in 15 minutes.

The queen bed has a comfortable Casper mattress just purchased last year, and two big south-facing windows let in tons of light, especially in the afternoon.  During your stay, I'll be sleeping in the living room on the couch. The couch is positioned so that it's facing the windows, away from rest of the apartment and away from the walkway from the bedroom to the kitchen. You're welcome to use the kitchen at any point during your stay. You have access to any and all dishes, glasses, and silverware, a kettle, pour-over coffee maker, a few varieties of tea, and regular and decaf coffee. The one bathroom in the apartment is right next to the bedroom, and getting to it does not require passing through the living room. I will provide soap, shampoo, and towels.

host_about:
I am a concert lighting designer out of the city I love deeply, Manhattan.  I have been here for a full ten years so as they say, it's official, I am a New Yorker!  I have been at this particular location for six years so it should be assumed that I am infatuated with my neighborhood.  I am usually working in strange places for long periods of time, or out on the streets trying to squeeze the city for all it's worth.  I do go to the gym quite a bit for health and vanity reasons, but mostly because I want to roll into 40yo with a decent situation lol.  I am an ex-record collector and music snob but have seriously lightened up since it became a full-time job of sorts. I just started dabbling in stand-up comedy because it terrifies me and also, why-not?  I live off the delicious food in my neighborhood and feed off the culture that is in abundance here.  I have turned myself into a person who chooses to see the positive before the negative as it is all too easy to turn into a cynical New Yorker.  I look forward to meeting you!


All best,
Eric

Ninth Avenue's constantly shifting array of multiethnic eateries draws theatergoers who shun Times Square's tourist traps. As gentrification takes hold, new apartment blocks are springing up in the former wasteland near the Hudson River—and development will kick into overdrive when the long-delayed mixed-use complex Hudson Yards and the last phase of the High Line finally come to fruition. neighborhood_overview: Hell’s Kitchen is a quintessential New York City neighborhood that runs along the beautiful Hudson River and sits just south of the world famous Central Park. It is home to intimate theaters, niche restaurants and lovely parks, like the Hudson River Park, whose well-manicured greenery makes a visit worthwhile.   Just west of the hustle and bustle of Times Square, you'll never have trouble hailing a cab, or getting a bartender's attention. The area is also ideal for biking, jogging and walking on foot. Community gardens also adorn the neighborhood.  Home of the American Late-Night Comedy Show, The Daily Show, as well as countless Zagat-rated eateries and bistros, Hell’s Kitchen is the best and brightest slice of New York City.
notes: You are going to have a lovely stay! I cannot wait to welcome you into my home!
transit: So close to New York City’s transportation hub, Times Square, there is nothing easier than getting around in Hell’s Kitchen.  On Foot: There are countless attractions just minutes away, including Broadway shows, Restaurant Row, Central Park, Hudson River Park and many more. NYC Subway: A five-minute walk to 47th Street & Broadway gets you access the N, Q and R trains. A three-minute walk to 46th Street & 8th Avenue gets you access to the A, C, E, 1,2,3, S and 7 trains.  On Bike: A one-minute walk to 45th Street & 8th Ave gets you access to NYC’s Citi Bike, a great and affordable way to bike around town.  By Car: In addition to many NYC taxis, there are several affordable private car services that traffic this area. Chat with me upon your arrival to receive great discounts on Lyft, Uber, Via and Gett, to name a few of the affordable private car services available in Hell’s Kitchen.
access: All guests will have unrestricted access to their private room, a shared bathroom, shared kitchen and scenic rooftop. Upon arrival, I’ll be sure to give you a guided tour of the building and the rooms to which you’ll have access.  It is my hope that you’ll feel at home during your stay. To that end, you are welcome to use any of the utensils you find in the kitchen area.
interaction: By New York City standards, I am a newbie. I have lived in the city for four years now and can still remember, vividly, how it felt to ride the subway for the first time, how it felt to get lost for the first time, and how relieved I was to have a stranger point me in the right direction. It is because of this that I make myself readily available for my guests.  If you have any questions about getting around NYC, things to see, places to eat, concerts to catch, I am happy to spend some time helping you out and making suggestions.  The better you understand what is available to you, the better your stay! I am here to help!
house_rules: You will be staying in a beautiful and quiet room in a friendly and respectful shared apartment. Your access to the kitchen and bathroom in this apartment will not be private. As this is the case, I ask that every guest: - Wipe any used surfaces thoroughly after use. A tidy home is a tidy mind. - Take out any trash or debris. Let's leave the rodents in the NYC subways. - Refrain from bringing outside guests unless confirmed with your hosts. We are friendly, but want to keep our home safe. - Refrain from using recreational drugs or throwing parties. There are so many nearby bars to have a good time. - Keep the noise level down after midnight. Cinderella needs her beauty rest. - Turn off the air conditioner, television, light fixture and any other appliances before leaving the apartment. The environment will thank you for it. Your room will also be located on the 4th Floor of this Pre-War building. Pre-War buildings are chock full of character. Lovely design and construction details run

Washington Heights is one of the few neighborhoods left in Manhattan with that real old New York feel - a wonderful multicultural mix of families, artists, kids, professionals, students, locals, and world travelers. My place is a hundred yards from stunning views of the George Washington bridge from Riverside Drive, on the edge of a genteel historic district called Audubon Terrace. Come stay in a wonderful safe green enclave just a few short blocks from the subway, with quick access to all the amenities of New York City, such as parks, bike paths, coffee shops, restaurants, and historic sites.

From our famous dollar oyster happy hours to the limitless champagne brunches, there's something for everyone on the LES.

host_about:
Am a 31 year old "almost" Florida native. I was born in Puerto Rico, but my family moved to a small town in Florida called Tallahassee which is where I was raised. I went to college at FSU and was first a Music Performance Major (French Horn), but later switched to a Fashion Merchandising Major which is what I hold my bachelor's degree in. 

I have recently just relocated to New York City and currently reside in the Upper East Side. I work for a luxury jewelry company on Fifth Avenue. 

I am currently single and will most likely be traveling alone, at most with a friend. I am fairly shy and quiet at first but tend to open up fairly quickly. I don't go out to bars much, but love a good restaurant and will be on my priority list of things to do when am in your city. Am also a huge music and movie buff. 

Now that I am turning 30 this year I have decided to do more traveling and find that Airbnb might be the most affordable way to go places I have yet to see. I have never used this before but I am excited to try this out and hope it all works out.

I have lived in NYC my entire life, and have been lucky enough to travel the world. Still every time my plane circles over this city preparing to land, I feel this burst of joy... because I'm home. There is no place like NY, it is one of the most amazing, whimsical, magical cities in the world. I love the idea of helping to share it with people, and  give them the opportunity to have the most comfortable,  convenient, local experience which allows them to truly explore what New York City is really about. As a creative professional, I enjoy great art, music, food, design, coffee, eclectic people, lazy weekends, and dancing all night. Luckily, this city has all or it. 
I take my hosting personally. I want guests to have a wonderful, stress-free time. I believe certain amenities and services are part of the bargain. I want the people who stay in my home to feel welcome, taken care of, mutually respected, and most importantly have fun.

summary: Welcome to the HART House! A safe and clean place for travelers and artists to sleep, rest, create, and get to know Spanish Harlem. The room has two bunk beds and comfortably sleeps four people.
space: The HART house is a gorgeous 5 bedroom, 2 bathroom apartment that is rented and run by the Harlem Art Collective. The apartment takes up the entire 5th floor of our building and is full of light, art, and creativity. Our walls are covered with murals and art from local artists and members of our collective, and we are always available to show you around the neighborhood and the art scene!  Our apartment is also a unique creative space that we use for art workshops, artist studio space, and Harlem Art Collective meetings and events, as well as a back packers haven and travelers hang out! Our guests are welcome and encouraged to tap into their creative side and paint or create art while staying with us!  The proceeds from your stay go directly into the the Harlem Art Collective to fund community based art projects, workshops, and cultural events. You can follow us on (website hidden)(email hidden) to see what projects we've already done!

neighborhood_overview: Spanish Harlem is an oasis in the hustle and bustle of Manhattan. Once you cross 3rd Ave and head East you feel life begin to slow down and the faces in the crowd begin to smile and say "hello". This neighborhood is one of the friendliest in New York, where everyone knows everyone's name. It is also one of the most diverse neighborhoods with a strong Puerto Rican and Dominican influence, peppered with African, West Indian, Mexican, African American, white, and Italian. History, art, culture, gastronomy, music, and a sense of style and class all it's own!
notes: **TAXES ARE NOT INCLUDED in the reservation. In New York City, Air bnb is legally not allowed to collect taxes on behalf of hosts, so taxes must be paid separately, either upon arrival or before. Taxes are 14.75%, and can be paid in cash, or with (SENSITIVE CONTENTS HIDDEN), Paypal, or Chase Quickpay.  **We have a cat! She is a short haired mix with low dander, but if you are allergic to cats please keep this in mind when making your reservation. Also, please be mindful of keeping windows and the front door closed at all times. ** Please keep in mind that New York City is a noisy place with a lot of people and smaller apartments than in the rest of the country. Our apartment is considered very big by NYC standards, but for non-New Yorkers the bedrooms will seem small and the street noise might be hard to get used to.  Also, we are on the 5th floor of a walk-up (meaning no elevator!). We have beautiful views of the city and access to our private rooftop, but please keep the 4 flights of
transit: We are three blocks from the 116th st stop on the 6 train. From our front door it is a 6 minute walk to the train. Once at the train station, it takes 15-20 minutes to get to downtown. We are a half a block from the M15 and M116 crosstown bus.  We are one block from the famous Patsy's Pizza! And one block from Jefferson Park! To get to us from JFK:  (1.5 hours) Take the Airtrain to Jamaica Center where you will catch the subway.  Take the E to Manhattan and get off at 53rd and Lexington  Transfer to the 6 uptown and get (email hidden)  Walk East for 3 blocks to 1st Ave  Turn right, we are half way down the block on the left To get to us from La Guardia:  (30 min) Take the M60 bus to Manhattan  Get off at 125th and 2nd Ave (the first stop in Manhattan)  Either walk to 1st Ave and 116th (we are between 115th and 116th on 1st Ave)  or take the M15 bus at 2nd Ave to 115th st and walk East one block to 1st Ave
access: We have all of the creature comforts for any traveler, including a living room with cable TV and wireless internet, a family-style dining room, a fully equipped kitchen with complimentary tea, and an awesome art studio-creative space for our guests to use.
interaction: We are an art collective made up of artists of all mediums, including painters, sculptors, musicians, and digital artists. Our goal with the HART House is to give travelers a friendly and authentic East Harlem experience, with true New Yorkers and Harlemites.  By hosting travelers we hope to promote cultural exchange and artistic collaboration between artists from all over the world and Harlem, as well as provide young tourists with a clean, safe, and affordable place to stay in one of the most culturally rich neighborhoods in New York City.  One or more of our members is always available to answer any of your questions, show you around the neighborhood, or recommend great places to eat and visit! We hope to learn as much from you as you learn from us!
house_rules: All of our rules are common sense:  -Clean up after yourself (*** recycle!!**** the bins are marked)  -Respect the other guests and residents of the HART HOUSE  -Be respectful of our neighbors (especially when walking up and down the stairs, please be very quiet!)  -Be respectful of the community of East Harlem  -Please let us know right away if anything needs repair -Quiet after 11pm  -No smoking in the house  -No pets  -Please turn off the lights and AC when you are not in the room  -Washer and dryer are not for guests (landlord will take it away!) -Have fun
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
I am a New York based painter, muralist, and street artist. I'm originally from Wisconsin, but I fell in love with Spanish Harlem when I moved here 6 years ago and have lived here ever since.
In april 2015, a group of fellow artists and I formed the Harlem Art Collective and since then we have done lots of public art projects and murals in the neighborhood, through these projects we have really gotten to know and love our neighbors and learn more about the history and culture of the neighborhood. Two of these artists, Diego and Alan, are current artists in residence at the Hart House and are always available to help you get the most out of your stay. We can recommend great places to eat, awesome events going on around the city, and tips for how to see and do what interests you most!

space: Welcome to NYC and my 'hood! I have lived in this apartment for over 15 years, and now that this neighborhood is up and coming (newly coined as NoMad), I'm happy that I stuck around. I hope you enjoy this fabulous area as much as I have enjoyed it over the years. About the apartment:  This is a 3-bedroom apartment, and I'm renting out the 3rd bedroom. The building is pre-war (built in 1890) and is located in historic Tin Pan Alley - a noted area of music & music publishing from the early 20th century. That being said this area and the building has a lot of character. There is an Italian restaurant on the ground level of the building as well as a spa on the first floor. You will proceed to the top of the stairwell to the 2nd floor.  Once you push through the "heavy" front door, you will enter into my oasis. neighborhood_overview: Aside from being located in a historic neighborhood, this area is a virtual hotbed of new activity! Because of its central location, new restaurants are opening all of the time, and the nightlife is picking up considerably.  The Ace Hotel is a block away, with the NoMad Hotel at the end of the block. Fairway Supermarket is 4 blocks away as well as the famed Eataly, and, if you love to shop, 5th Avenue shopping is down the street in the Flatiron district, as well as Macy's and Herald Square shopping in the opposite direction. Even Times Square is just a short subway ride (2 stops) or 20-minute walk away. You can stroll through Madison Square Square Park to view the lovely art installations or just people watch ... or head on over to the Highline to get a bird's eye view of the city landscape.  We're moving on up here!
notes: I do have a beautiful tuxedo cat, Oreo, who is very playful and extremely friendly to all (even new guests she has not met - she's like a puppy dog). She loves attention! But if you do suffer from cat allergies, this place is not for you. Also, there is a 20 fee for a lost set of keys, which will be taken from the deposit.
transit: The one thing that everyone always says about where I live: It's so easy to travel around and get to Manhattan and even Brooklyn and Queens from here. Here are your options: N/R Train @ 28th St  Stop: at the end of my block 6 Train @ 28th St Stop: just 2 blocks away 1 Train @ 28th St Stop: just 2 blocks away B/D/F/M & Path Train @ Herald Square Stop: 5 min walk 5th Avenue bus stop is located around the corner on 5th Ave between 28th and 29th Streets. Penn Station is a 10-minute walk away, and Grand Central is about 20 minutes (or 2 subway stops).
access: You will have access to all of the apartment with the exception of the other two bedrooms.
interaction: I stay in one of the bedrooms. I will be in and out of the apartment but I will always be available to assist you in any way during your stay. Just ask! (Directions around the city, restaurant recommendations, places to visit, etc.) However, I will be extremely respectful of your privacy whenever you need it.
house_rules: - General courtesy and cleanliness expected.  - Be respectful of our neighbors, no rowdiness.  - Absolutely no smoking in the apartment. - No outside pets. - Do not bring guests to the apartment without clearing it with me beforehand. In addition, no sleepover guests allowed.

neighborhood_overview: The Lower East Side is Manhattan’s most eclectic grit-meets-glam neighborhood. Probably best known for the slew of trendy bars and lounges that sprung up in the early 2000’s (most of which remain alive and well), the Lower East Side also has a funky mix of trendy boutiques, mom-and-pop shops, cozy cafes, and chic restaurants. With longtime residents and first-generation hipsters welcoming a new wave of students and young professionals to the area, the diverse population continues to grow. The Lower East Side stretches east from the Bowery to the East River Park. It is bordered on the north by Houston Street and the south by Canal Street and East Broadway.

St. Mark's Place is the hub of the East Village, close to all transportation (for east or west side) and NYU, Cooper Union. host_about:
We're a Tennessee boy and Seattle gal who traded the rainy days and country hills for city thrills, vowing to learn the constant lessons of an adventurous and passionate life. 

Traveling is, by far, our favorite thing to do. We believe it's essential to a fulfilling life. Mark Twain said it best — “Twenty years from now you will be more disappointed by the things you didn’t do than by the ones you did do. So throw off the bowlines, sail away from the safe harbor. Catch the trade winds in your sails. Explore. Dream. Discover.”

Our list of places we've traveled covers the globe, including Ireland (where Matt's relatives are from), Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Yellowstone National Park, Whistler British Columbia, Hungary, Germany, Kenya, Galapagos Islands, New Zealand, Australia, Thailand, Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam, Dominican Republic, Puerto Rico, Mexico, all of western Europe, Morocco and so many more to come... 

In between trips, Matt works as a creative director at an advertising agency, while Allie runs her own interior design firm (thus our place has a professional designer's personal touch!)

neighborhood_overview: The apartment is located in an area of the Upper East side once known as the silk stocking district, also known as Yorkville. The apartment is across the street from an elementary school and is next door to a luxury high rise, it is considered a very safe area of NYC. There is a Duane Reade pharmacy on the corner of our street -2 min walk, also on our street you can find a nail salon and an Irish pub. There are several 24-hour convenience stores around the corner. Many different kinds of restaurants are within a 5 min walk (including a Michelin rated restaurant). There is a Starbucks coffee one block away and a small leisure city park one block from the apartment.  The closest subway is a ten minute walk, there are also yellow cabs driving by the apartment at all hours.
notes: The apartment has security cameras and live security intercom for any guests or deliveries. It will light up when someone is outside the door and will show you a live video of the street.
transit: The 4/5/6 trains are a ten min walk from the apartment. You can walk to 96street or 86street. There is also the 2nd avenue bus which is a 3 min walk from the apartment.

neighborhood_overview: Harlem is known internationally as the Mecca of the African diaspora, but Harlem has been home to many different identities including the Dutch, Irish, German, Italian, and Jewish. Harlem was originally settled by the Dutch in 1658, but was largely farmland and undeveloped territory for approximately 200 years. As New York’s population grew, residential and commercial expansion moved northward, and development of the Harlem territory was inevitable. During the 1880’s, elevated rail lines were extended north along Eight & Ninth Avenues, encouraging expansion northward. Development of transportation lines caused speculation on the land and many fine row houses and multiple family apartment buildings were erected. However, this boom slowed in 1893 when a national recession struck. The recession curbed further developed and stymied real estate sales. When the economy recovered in 1895, development continued, especially in the form of beautiful apartment buildings. Located on 123rd street,

neighborhood_overview: The apartment is on the border of both the Lower East Side and on the edges of Chinatown. The apt is on the first floor. The Lower East Side is now one of Manhattan’s most fashionable neighborhoods. Most of the bargain-clothing stores and pickle vendors have given way to indie boutiques and sceney eateries, though there are a few cherished survivors of the former Jewish stronghold, including venerable smoked-fish purveyors Russ & Daughters and pastrami legend Katz’s Delicatessen. The Tenement Museum keeps the neighborhood’s history alive in a series of restored apartments visited via themed guided tours, but most of the area’s cultural draws are contemporary: The arrival of the New Museum on the Bowery several years ago drew numerous art galleries to the LES. Take a walk in the area south of Broome Street and east of Lafayette, and you’ll be in Chinatown. neighborhood_overview: Washington Heights is a quiet, serene place and the perfect home base in a city that can sometimes be frantic. Across the street from my building is the beautiful J. Hood Wright Park and views of the George Washington bridge. Home to families, people in the performing arts, and doctors and nurses who work at nearby NYP, the neighborhood has a residential feel. There are grocery and convenience stores on almost every block along Broadway, including Gristedes, Key Food, Bravo, and Rosa's.  Saggio, Coogan's, and Le Cheile are the best bars/restaurants in the neighborhood. For most nightlife you're probably going to want to stay downtown, but you'll be home in a snap on the express train.
transit: The A express train is less than two blocks from my front door and will take you to Times Square in 20-30 minutes. The 1 line is within walking distance, too, and can get you to the Upper West Side/Central Park in 15-20 minutes.  There is a parking garage 4 blocks from the apartment where you can park for about 25 a day. There's also plenty of street parking.

neighborhood_overview: Historically, the Lower East Side was a stopping ground for immigrants who just arrived in NYC and was filled with tenements. There is an awesome Tenement Museum now on Orchard street, not far from my apartment. The Lower East Side has, in my opinion, two identities. The eastern side is very residential. The western, more in part is a hip, night time destinations with many bars, restaurants, galleries, cafes, independent shops, etc. My apartment is a couple of minutes from the hip part.  My particular street is very much in transition definitely going through gentrification. My block has now three renovated buildings, including mine and I suspect in a few years, will be completely different.  My immediate neighborhood is a mix of people - a real reflection of NYC diversity - Asian, Latin, Jewish, Black, young professionals, hipsters, artists, etc. It's a cool mix. The street is urban for sure but very safe. My building is filled with young professionals, creative types - one married co
notes: This is my personal apartment. It's not a business. It's not a hotel. It's not perfect. I host often and keep up with my place because of that. I try to keep it as clean as possible. However, it does have imperfections like anyone's home. If you expect perfection, it's best you book a hotel. :)
transit: F train, East Broadway stop is seconds away, very convenient and per my reviews, one of the things people love about my place.  The East Broadway stop is the last stop in Manhattan before it heads to Dumbo in Brooklyn The F train also goes up the center of Manhattan and can take you to the East Village, Soho, West Village, Chelsea, Time Square, Rockefeller Center and the southern part of Central Park. It's the best train! :)
access: Guests have access to the whole apartment.
interaction: As we will be sharing the apartment, interaction is a given. I will definitely give you as much privacy and quiet time as needed, but I am also always available for pleasant conversation and if have time, up for beers and hanging out.

neighborhood_overview: Our apartment is located in Washington Heights/Ft George area in the rolling hills of upper Manhattan. The building is on top of a hill overlooking Broadway down below and the beautiful Fort Tryon Park is located across on the opposite hill. The winding paths of this park house the impressive Cloisters, a building constructed by the Rockefeller family and donated to the city of New York and now managed by the Metropolitan Museum. Nestled in the park nearby is the Green Leaf Cafe which is a wonderful brunch spot.  The park boasts a beautiful view of the Hudson River and especially the George Washington Bridge which crosses from New Jersey into Manhattan at 181st Street. The demographics of the area include a strong Jewish community and the Yeshiva University is only two blocks away as well as families from the Dominican Republic. Here you will find numerous restaurants and markets that provide that Caribbean flavor of cuisine. So brush up on your Spanish! We are also located across the
transit: There are two subway lines that access downtown. The closest is the 1 Train (or Red Line) at the 191st Street Station on St. Nicholas Avenue. This is a short 3-4 minute walk. A little farther, about a 10-12 minute walk, will get you to the A Train (or Blue Line) at the 181st Street Station (with an entrance on 184th Street). This train is the Express train and can get you to Times Square in only 20-25 minutes. My personal commute to 14th Street takes about 35 minutes door to door. There are also local private car services that we utilize and they will negotiate a price for you. We have their telephone numbers available for you. Taxis are more limited in this area, but here you will find the new GREEN taxis which service the outer-boroughs of Manhattan. However, the subway is by far the fastest and easiest mode of transportation to most locations.

neighborhood_overview: OUR HARLEM NEIGHBORHOOD: We love our neighborhood--I (Abby) first moved here in 2010 for grad school and it just keeps getting better! We are located in South Harlem - just 9 blocks from Central Park, in an area now affectionately being called "SoHa".  It's funky and diverse, with lots of history and character, and the streets are very broad and well-lit so it's easy and safe to walk around, even at night.  CAFES, BARS, RESTAURANTS: There are lots of shops, cafes, bakeries, bistros, wine bars, beer gardens, and night clubs all within a 10 block radius, and there's always something new to check out. HISTORIC HARLEM: We are surrounded by Harlem brownstones, gospel churches, and old jazz clubs. The Apollo Theater, Minton's Playhouse and Showman's all only a few blocks away. Also close by is the Studio Museum of Harlem, and Celebrity Chef Marcus Samuelsson's restaurant, Red Rooster. Make sure to check out our Neighborhood Guidebook to see all the nearby shops, bars, and restaurants! A SHOR
notes: We provide organic coffee and local teas. We are also able to provide breakfast, just let us know upon booking. If you have any questions or needs, please ask! We want your stay to meet or exceed your expectations. We do have a somewhat flexible check-in policy, but we also have full time jobs and may not be able to let you in during work hours (8-6 pm), or we may be able to arrange for you to get the key without meeting us. Please let us know your travel plans and we'll work hard to accommodate you and make your arrival smooth.
transit: Local trains (B, C) are 3 blocks away. Express trains (A, D) are 5 blocks away. We're also very close to the 2,3 trains at 116th. Trains to midtown are a quick 15 minute ride. Inexpensive public transportation from LaGuardia airport is extremely convenient here.

host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
Hey there!

I'm Abby, married to Eric, and we're happy to host and travel using Airbnb.

A little about us: 

I (Abby) teach English to international students at New York University (NYU).  I love languages and years ago spent some time abroad studying Spanish in Sevilla, Spain. 

I love to cook and entertain, and I enjoy running here in Central Park. I also love to read when I have time. In NY, I seek out good sample sales in the city. Feel free to ask me about them.

Eric, my husband, is a Texan who is a musician/philosopher/technical writer. He works at a software company but would probably rather be playing guitar or reading math books. He likes open spaces and mountain landscapes. 

When we spend time together in the city, we love to explore new neighborhoods on foot with our dog, Ike, or take bike rides along the Hudson River. We also like to listen to live music, especially jazz. 

When we travel, we try to pack light and hit the town. We like to take in a few things slowly, rather than trying to jam-pack a day.

neighborhood_overview: Central Harlem is relaxed and spacious compared to rest of Manhattan.  Boulevards are wide and residents are friendly.  In recent years, many abandoned homes have been renovated (such as ours) and in response, new and exciting restaurants and shops seem to open every month.  Bed Bath&Beyond just opened a block away and Whole Foods Market is opening in the summer of 2017.  I have a list of local restaurant and store recommendations in the apartment.   Harlem is a gentrifying neighborhood.  It is not the Upper East Side, and we wouldn't want it to be.  Our family has been living here for two years, and many of our neighbors have been here for generations.  This block is lively in the summertime, and you should expect to see people gathering on the side walk enjoying music and conversation in the evenings.  Things generally quiet down after 11 pm.  Overall, the street noise here is typical for New York City.  In cooler weather, it is quieter that commercial streets. I am often asked if it
notes: No TV.  No Elevator.  Free wi-fi, tea, coffee and filtered water.  The convenience center is not a kitchen and does not have a sink or a stove.  It is intended for enjoying take-out, snacks and drinks.  Dishes and utensils are available.   Our townhouse is located on a beautiful residential block.  The amount of street noise is typical for New York City, but gets louder in the summer with the socializing on the stoops.  Please bring ear plugs if you are not used to it.
transit: This townhouse is easily accessible from all major points in Manhattan. Subways: The closest subway stop is right around the corner, a 3 min. walk away -- the 2/3 express stop at W. 125 St. and Lenox (or Malcolm X Blvd).  The 2/3 trains stop at the Upper West Side (Lincoln Center), Times Square (Broadway district), Penn Station, Chelsea, One World Trade Center, Wall Street, and Brooklyn.  A 15 min. walk to the west is the ABCD subway for Central Park West, The Natural History Museum, and Columbus Circle.  A 15 min. walk to the east is the 4/5/6 line for the Upper East Side, Grand Central, Union Square, and the East Village.   Buses: The M60 express bus stops on W. 125 St. at Lenox and goes to/from LaGuardia Airport.  The M102 bus stops on Lenox at W. 124 St. and travels to the Upper East Side, Central Park Zoo, and the Met and Guggenheim Museums on 5th Avenue.   Other: Taxis can be hailed from the cross streets Lenox and Adam Clayton Powell.  Parking and rental cars are available at ga

host_about:
Blessed with our little girl Samantha, we strive to be better people everyday with the little things in life.  We used to run thru the nightclubs and live the crazy lifestyle...we couldn't live without late night movies, the latest bar/lounge/club, being in "THE IT" crowd, running off to Paris or a quick trip to Vegas at a moments notice for a few days!  

Funny, but we now get up at dawn and love to go to the Zoo, reading, although presently its all about Dr. Seuss's "Hop on Pop", and walking thru the city and exploring all the different neighborhoods.  We  enjoy going to ethnic restaurants and exploring tastes while exposing our girl to all NYC has to offer.  

As we are a mixed couple, living within this diverse city gives us a sense of home that we cherish.  We are a small family with a HUGE extended family that live in the New York and Maryland area and work hard developing our relationships with our family.  

When we travel we appreciate a host that welcomes us like family, but stays out of our business.  Thats what you can expect from us.  We want to be available to you if you need, but otherwise, enjoy your privacy and have fun.  We believe that being a good person is crucial and that good things happen to good people.  That is what we are....good people.

summary: Your private bedroom in our apartment will be your home away from home! With easy subway access, you're just 25 minutes from Times Square and the surrounding areas. Come visit and see all NYC has to offer without breaking the bank on accommodations!
space: Your private room will be comfortable and relaxing, furnished with everything you need for a great stay. It includes a full size (double) bed, two bed-side tables, a large dresser, full size mirror, and large closet. We've collected a large assortment of NYC guidebooks and other publications so if you're looking for unique, "only in New York" activities, we've got you covered! Our apartment is ideal because of its close proximity to the subway as well as sights to see off the "beaten path."  Our large apartment will provide plenty of room for up to 2 people to stretch out, relax, and enjoy your time in the city!  Look out our living room window and you'll see Sylvan Terrace, a historic cobblestone block that once served as the carriageway to the Morris-Jumel Mansion, Manhattan’s oldest house and George Washington's headquarters during much of the Revolutionary War. neighborhood_overview: Washington Heights is a perfect mix of "city life" but with a great neighborhood feel. Walk one block up to the Morris-Jumel Mansion and you are transported to another time that's quiet and relaxing. Conversely, walk one block over to Broadway and the hustle and bustle of New York truly comes alive. Within one block of our apartment is a laundromat, grocery store, liquor store, Rite Aid and numerous restaurants. We're happy to point you in the direction of anything you might need to pick up while you're here.
notes: We have three wonderful pets that live here as well. Rusty the dog and the two cats Pickles and Hamilton will greet you when you arrive to our home. They are fun-loving and cuddly but we will make sure you only interact with them as much as you're comfortable with.
transit: The only way that transportation could be more convenient is if we lived INSIDE a train station. (Don't worry, we don't). Come up from the subway and our front door is in plain view. Simply take the C train to the 163rd/Amsterdam stop and you're here! Rest assured however that because it's underground, the noise of the train is a non-issue.  For bus service, the stop around the corner provides access to the M3, M100, and M101 so if you're looking to stay above ground you're covered there as well!  If you're bringing a car, free parking all around our building is also incredibly convenient with "street sweeping" only happening once a week. We have learned all the tricks to parking so we will be happy to pass those along should you need. Getting here from the airports is fairly simple. LaGuardia is the closest, and is a 15-minute cab ride away (when there is no traffic). It should only cost about 35. With public transportation simply take the M60 Select Bus Service to 125th St/Frederick
access: As our guests, you have access to anything you need in the bedroom, kitchen, bathroom, and living room. You'll get clean linens and basic amenities should you need them. In addition, password-protected Wi-Fi is accessible throughout the apartment. In the living room we have a flatscreen TV with Blu Ray, Apple TV, and HBO which you're welcome to use. We also have a nice selection of movies on hand as well as a large selection of exercise DVDs and equipment if you need to squeeze in a workout!  Our kitchen is large and includes a full-size refrigerator, gas stove/oven, microwave, french-press, blender and a vast array of kitchen supplies and utensils. It also boasts a table that is set up for 2 but which will expand to seat up to 4.  The bathroom is large and has plenty of space for toiletries. We have a shower/tub, with ample hot water and excellent water pressure. Towels and washcloths are provided. Overall, we want to take the worry out of your trip so anything we can provide, we will
interaction: Our schedule varies quite a bit, but rest assured that when we are at home, we love to get to know our guests! We encourage you to use the apartment like a roommate might. Sit and watch some Netflix with us and crack open a bottle of wine if you like. That being said, we know you're not coming to New York to see us, so please don't feel obligated to spend your valuable vacation time on us.
house_rules: Check in is after 3 pm (depending on our availability) and check out is by 11 am. If you need to leave luggage that is a possibility, just let us know and we will try our very best to accommodate you!  Common courtesy is our most important rule. We expect everyone, (including ourselves), to be mutually respectful of the common space. This includes cleaning up our own messes, washing our own dishes, and keeping the living room, kitchen, and bathroom tidy and comfortable. We expect our animals to be treated humanely, safely, and lovingly. We request that they not be fed human food, no matter how cute they are or how long Rusty gives you his heart-melting "puppy dog" eyes.  No smoking inside the apartment. Tobacco, or anything else... We love to meet people, but inviting guests of guests into our home is something we'd rather not do. We're sure your friends are awesome, but please respect our home and meet them for dinner and drinks down the street, not in the apartment.  In general, our

neighborhood_overview: Hell's Kitchen/Clinton is by far the best dining district in Midtown Manhattan. 9th Ave. is lined with local hotspots, both restaurants and bars. Great for Pre-Theatre. And for the budget conscious, you can get cheap Chinese, Punjabi, and Mexican food on 10th Ave. Apt. is nearby: Times Square, all Broadway Theaters (easily "rush" for cheap tix), TKTS, David Letterman (standby "rush"), Madison Square Garden (sports games and concerts), Rockefeller Center (Top of The Rock, NBC Studio Store), Lincoln Center (Met Opera, NYC Ballet), Central Park, and Hudson River Bike Path (rent a bike and ride). Near two popular bars: 123 Burger Shot Beer and Waylon (country bar). Nearish: The Highline Park, Chelsea Market, Museum of Natural History (think "Night At The Museum"), MoMA (modern art), and more. Also great for auditioning actors, dancers, and musicians (near to Actors Equity Building, Ripley Grier, Alvin Ailey, Chelsea Studios).
transit: All Access to Subways: blue ACE, red 123, yellow NRQ, orange BDFM via M50 Crosstown Bus (the stop is around the corner). Virtual connection to anywhere as far as Battery Park (Statue of Liberty), 911 Memorial, Harlem 125th St. and anything in between. Easily shoot up to Westchester via Grand Central. You Can Get Anywhere, trust me on this. Getting to/from here from the Airport? - (URL HIDDEN) runs cheap buses to/from JFK & LaGuardia The Port Authority (9 blocks away) for 14-16. Cheap cab from there to the Apt. - CoachUSA runs a bus to/from EWR from The Port Authority for 16. I walk to the terminal all the time when I travel. (URL HIDDEN) - Taxis to/from JFK are a flat 65.00, LGA is about 45, Newark-EWR varies but its much more expensive in rush hour - Shuttles include Airlink (white van) and  SuperShuttle (blue van). 1.5 hours travel time but only 20-23. - Public Transit: JFK - Airtrain to Jamaica Station in Queens, transfer to Subway - Blue Line E "towards Manhattan" to 50th St.

It’s the neighborhood where tourists and New Yorkers go any day of the week to have a beer or grab dinner with friends. Or they just sit down in one of the small cafes or Washington Square Park where anytime of the day different street musicians perform. Tourist Tip: You can take some awesome pictures in front of the Washington Square fountain with the Washington Square Arch and the Empire State building in the background. :)
